GaAsN has been extensively studied for semiconductor lasers for optical-fiber communication in the wavelength range. GaAsN has a wide optical region coverage from the near infrared to the ultraviolet region, where the optical properties can be tailored as GaN and GaAs semiconductors. It is also highlighted that the smaller nitrogen will cause a big bandgap reduction, which causes GaAsN to have lower a bandgap value as compared to GaAs. For instance, 1% of nitrogen incorporation can contribute to a 0.2 eV bandgap reduction.179 In 2000, Uesugi et al.101 studied the absorption coefficient of GaAs0.9966N0.0034 and GaAs0.992N0.008 using the T method at 25 K and 297 K. The α2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
